A couple of years ago, we did a spotlight on 1984 Anoka High Hchool graduate Eric Gieseke, who at the time was chief of the Burnsville Police Department (read it here: https://bit.ly/3lX8k2V).

We're following up because it turns out Gieseke has retired from the force and has launched a post-police career as director of TAGS Gymnastics, which has locations in Apple Valley and Eden Prairie. It's a perfect fit, too, because Gieseke was a state champion gymnast at Anoka, and then competed at the University of Wisconsin - Madison. Sun Thisweek Newspapers has more about his new career. #AHSchools

post_text:
Teachers and staff returned to buildings across Anoka-Hennepin on Sept. 1 ready to hit the ground running for the 2020-21 school year. At Coon Rapids Middle School, English language arts teachers teamed up to create a synchronous classroom simulation involving both hybrid and distance learners.

Tyler Schmidt, an English teacher at CRMS, was the classroom teacher for the simulation. During the event, he welcomed mock students (other CRMS teachers) into the classroom to sit at socially-distanced desks, and began class by welcoming in-person and distance learning students via Google Meet.

Meanwhile, in a second-floor classroom, another group of CRMS teachers were playing the role of distance learning students, participating in the classroom discussion through Google Meet, while also completing lessons through pre-recorded material. View photos and learn more about the Return to School Roadmap:https://bit.ly/2F8fNuM

The livestream of the Anoka-Hennepin School Board meeting on Aug. 24 is experiencing technical difficulties. Technicians are working on restoring the signal and the board recessed the meeting to allow time to fix the issue. After a 20 minute delay, the board resumed the meeting with the intent of restoring the stream. Viewers should know that the meeting is available on Comcast Cable Channel 18 in Blaine, Ham Lake, Coon Rapids, Anoka, Andover, Champlin and Ramsey.

Tonight's meeting is being recorded and will be available to view on the district website Tuesday.

We apologize for the issue. #AHSchools

post_text:
ICYMI: Tim Riordan, the life sciences teacher at Blaine High School, recently received a grant for Outdoor adventures, which is a popular environmental science class offered at Anoka-Hennepin’s five traditional high schools that often introduces students to ice fishing, camping, hiking and other outdoor activities.

Riordan said he’s noticed an alarming trend: enrollment in the winter trimester of the class is about 45 percent lower than the fall and spring offerings. And he’s pretty sure he knows why: winter activities cost a lot more.

In January, Riordan applied for an $11,550 state grant to help offset some of those winter activity costs. In June he learned he and the school got the grant! Read more about outdoor adventures and the opportunities the grant will help provide. #AHSchools

post_text: Congratulations to Kathryn VanArragon, a sophomore at Blaine High School, who won the 2020 Minnesota Women's State Open on Aug. 11, finishing a 4-over-par 146 (73-73) becoming the youngest winner in event history. Watch VanArragon's highlights from the tournament: https://youtu.be/5om6EA36VR8
shared_text:
Minnesota PGA
August 11 at 3:53 PM ·

Kathryn VanArragon is our 2020 Minnesota Women’s State Open winner! She shot 73-73-146 to take the title over the Round 1 leader Taylor Ledwein by one stroke.

Kathryn is also the youngest winner of the Minnesota Women’s State Open ever! The previous youngest winner was Sarah Burnham when she won in 2013.

Lisa Grimes took home low professional honors, shooting 72-76-148 and finishing T3 overall.

Thank you to everyone who played in this year’s Minnesota Women’s State Open, and thank you so much to the staff and crew at The Jewel Golf Club for hosting us this week!

Full Leaderboard: https://mnpga.bluegolf.com/bluegolf/mnpga20/event/mnpga2027/contest/1/leaderboard.htm?1234

post_text:
Outdoor adventures is a popular environmental science class offered at Anoka-Hennepin’s five traditional high schools that often introduces students to ice fishing, camping, hiking and other outdoor activities.

But Tim Riordan, the life sciences education teacher at Blaine High School who teaches the class, said he’s noticed an alarming trend: enrollment in the winter trimester of the class is about 45 percent lower than the fall and spring offerings. And he’s pretty sure he knows why: winter activities cost a lot more.

In January, Riordan applied for an $11,550 state grant to help offset some of those winter activity costs. In June he learned he and the school got the grant! Read more about outdoor adventures and the opportunities the grant will help provide. #AHSchools

Anoka-Hennepin is excited to introduce the Parent Engage 360 podcast series, where district and state experts will discuss parenting topics such as mental health, chemical health, internet safety and more.

In the second episode, Liz Burgard, Anoka-Hennepin Parent Involvement Coordinator, discusses chemical health topics and parenting tips with Colleen O'Neil, Anoka-Hennepin Schools Chemical Health Prevention Specialist, and Kjirsten Anderson, Regional Alcohol Tobacco and Other Drugs Prevention Coordinator.

Discover what parents need to know about chemical health, especially during COVID-19, i.e. warning signs, conversation starters, resources, and ways to support their child.

Read more about the Parent Engage 360 podcast series, and listen to the latest episode: https://bit.ly/2CAgyeY

post_text: Are you looking for something to do this week? Check out swimming lessons from Anoka-Hennepin Community Education, held at Northdale Middle School. Sessions are offered by week, and there is still just a little time to enroll in classes running this Monday-Thursday: www.ahschools.us/swim.
shared_text:
Roosevelt Community Pool
July 6 at 12:41 PM ·

Anoka-Hennepin Community Education is now offering limited aquatic programs, following health and safety recommendations from the Minnesota department of health (MDH) and the United States Centers for Disease Control (CDC).

Safety is our top priority, and staff will be cleaning all aquatic equipment including kick boards or diving rings between uses. Aquatic programs have been modified and instructors have been trained in following social distance guidelines in the pool. The number of participants in each class is limited, and we ask that only one adult accompany each child for observation to minimize the number of people in the pool and on the pool deck or bleachers.

Learn more about how we are re-opening safely, and register for current aquatic programs including youth swimming lessons: https://www.ahschools.us/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=47&ModuleInstanceID=29791&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=81220&PageID=87

The Anoka-Hennepin School District is participating in the Summer Food Service Program (SFSP) once again this summer. Meals are being provided to all children 18 and under, free of charge.

Meals are provided on a first-come, first-serve basis, at 13 sites across the district from 11 a.m. to 12 p.m. daily. Meals will not be available on Friday, July 3, but two days' worth of meals will be provided on July 2. Services will resume July 6. Visit our website for more information, including an interactive map of all 13 sites: https://bit.ly/3eFGYKC

Anoka-Hennepin is excited to introduce the Parent Engage 360 podcast series, where district and state experts will discuss parenting topics such as mental health, chemical health, internet safety and more.

In the first podcast episode, join Liz Burgard, Anoka-Hennepin Parent Involvement Coordinator, as she discusses mental health topics and parenting tips with Sue Abderholden, Executive Director of NAMI Minnesota, and Megan Lagasse, Anoka-Hennepin School Social Worker. In particular, discover what parents need to know about mental health, especially during COVID-19, i.e. warning signs, conversation starters, resources and ways to support their child. Read more about the Parent Engage 360 podcast series, and listen to the first episode: https://bit.ly/3frSIjJ | #AHSchools

Anoka-Hennepin is excited to introduce the Parent Engage 360 podcast series, where district and state experts will discuss parenting topics such as mental health, chemical health, internet safety and more.

In the first podcast episode, join Liz Burgard, Anoka-Hennepin Parent Involvement Coordinator, as she discusses mental health topics and parenting tips with Sue Abderholden, Executive Director of NAMI Minnesota, and Megan Lagasse, Anoka-Hennepin School Social Worker. In particular, discover what parents need to know about mental health, especially during COVID-19, i.e. warning signs, conversation starters, resources and ways to support their child. Read more about the Parent Engage 360 podcast series, and listen to the first episode: https://bit.ly/3frSIjJ | #AHSchools

Anoka-Hennepin families needing support with meals during the summer:

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a temporary food benefit program for students who are normally able to get free or reduced-price school meals. Qualifying families can apply and get up to $325 per child to spend on groceries. This program is operated through the Minnesota Department of Human Services, the Minnesota Department of Education and Code for America. Applications must be completed by June 30. Apply here: https://bit.ly/37hmMfb

More information about the P-EBT program is available here: https://bit.ly/3heMRjt

For more information about where you can find summer meals (regardless of whether or not you qualify for free or reduced-price meals) on our website: https://bit.ly/37n6e5h

At the request of state officials and in cooperation with law enforcement and public safety partners, Anoka-Hennepin schools is ensuring community members are aware that temporary curfews are in place for all Anoka County and the cities of Brooklyn Park, Brooklyn Center and Champlin in the Hennepin County portions of the district.

These temporary curfews are in place for all persons starting Saturday, May 30 and Sunday, May 31 from 8 p.m. to 6 a.m. each day as a safety measure.

Thank you for your understanding of the school district’s role as a partner in ensuring safety for students and the greater community.

post_text:
Let’s Talk About It! - Helping Our Seniors by Colleen O'Neil, LADC, CPP, Anoka-Hennepin's chemical health prevention specialist. This month’s topic was going to be about summer and the freedom that many of our students would have experienced, with a focus on prom, graduation parties, and other milestones students often partake in had it not been for COVID-19.

While the pandemic continues to unfold around us, I want to spend some time focusing on our graduating seniors and the sense of loss (and grief) that each of them may be experiencing. It’s important to make sure that our seniors feel supported in their feelings and that they have healthy coping skills in place to avoid any negative consequences that could lead to substance use and misuse, mental health problems or family issues. Read the full blog post and learn about available resources: https://bit.ly/2yqKubH

Distance learning "coaching" tips from Community Ed staff

Anoka-Hennepin Community Education
May 4 at 4:03 PM ·

Community education staff at Anoka-Hennepin School District middle schools coordinate a wide variety of enrichment classes, activities and sports for students after-school, year-round - but coaching looks different this spring season. "What we are experiencing is new to everyone," Jenna Zabel, Anoka Middle School Community Schools coordinator, said. "We want to remind everyone to be kind to themselves and others."

As families and students prepare to continue distance learning through the remainder of the school year, Community Schools coordinators offer "coaching" tips for motivation and encouragement.

Watch a video summary of all of the tips on the Anoka-Hennepin Community Education YouTube channel: https://youtu.be/4jhA9nv_Uac

Read the full article on our website: https://bit.ly/2W3WMjb

post_text:
Meals update: Friday, May 1 and Monday, May 4, were directed through the state order to be professional development days with the goal of supporting the needs of teachers to improve and refine distance learning practices. Although no distance learning instruction will be held these days, meals will be provided at the regularly scheduled time on both days. Meals will be served from 11 a.m. to 12:30 p.m.

During pickup time, children will be provided a bag lunch as well as a bag breakfast meal for the following morning. Meals will be distributed through the passenger side window of vehicles from school buses. More information on grab-and-go meals and pickup locations is available at https://www.ahschools.us/covid-19meals

In case you missed it: Three years ago, Anoka High School launched its STEAM (science, technology, engineering, arts, and mathematics) program. This year, a pioneering group of five seniors are set to complete their last required STEAM course: Honors Design and Development.

For this capstone course, the students researched and designed prototype solutions to address the problem of waste reduction. The group then presented their prototype concepts to a small professional review panel via Google Hangouts on April 17.

Learn more about the capstone projects and what the experience has been like for students: https://bit.ly/3bZNlGY | #AHSchools #AHDistanceLearning

post_text:
Three years ago, Anoka High School launched its STEAM (science, technology, engineering, arts, and mathematics) program. This year, a pioneering group of five seniors are set to complete their last required STEAM course: Honors Design and Development.

For this capstone course, the students researched and designed prototype solutions to address the problem of waste reduction. The group then presented their prototype concepts to a small professional review panel via Google Hangouts on April 17.

Learn more about the capstone projects and what the experience has been like for students.

post_text:
Meals update for the Coon Rapids cluster of schools: Starting tomorrow, Thursday, April 23, the meal distribution site at Coon Rapids High School will be moved to Coon Rapids Middle School due to Fit for the Future construction projects that will be ramping up at the high school. Meals will continue to be served daily (M-F) from 11 a.m. to 12:30 p.m.

During pickup time, children will be provided a bag lunch as well as a bag breakfast meal for the following morning. Meals will be distributed through the passenger side window of vehicles from school buses. More information on grab-and-go meals is available at https://www.ahschools.us/covid-19meals

It's National Volunteer Recognition Week! All of our volunteers have made an enormous impact in our community. This past year, over 16,995 volunteers contributed over 290,812 hours toward developing, supporting, and enhancing a variety of programs both in our schools and our communities.

Even though schools are functioning differently in these challenging times, many volunteers have still been reaching out, asking how they can share their time and talents to support our schools, our staff and our students. post_text:
Check out the latest chemical health blog, written by Colleen O'Neil, LADC, CPP, Anoka-Hennepin School District Chemical Health Prevention Specialist. Let's Talk About It: Spiraling out of control?

No one has been spared from the COVID-19 pandemic. No one. Each one of us will forever remember the challenges, the sacrifices, and the fear that we faced while learning new phrases such as social distancing, COVID-19, and distance learning to name a few.

This pandemic has forced us to make decisions we may not have had to make prior, and this applies to our teens as well. The inability to be with friends, to go to school, or to attend those functions that are all part of the high school experience — it’s been forever altered and changed. This can have a huge impact on one’s mental health and for some — on their substance use. Read the full blog post: https://bit.ly/2OUzHLP

post_text:
Update on Anoka-Hennepin’s “grab and go” meal program: Starting April 3, Anoka-Hennepin has added four new meal distribution sites. Food will continue to be distributed from school buses located at the sites designated as meal pickup locations. No identification or registration will be required in alignment with program guidelines.

On April 9, children will receive two days' worth of meals as services will be suspended on April 10, which is a designated non-school day for students. Meal distribution will resume on April 13. More information, including addresses and an interactive map with all 36 sites, can be found at https://www.ahschools.us/covid-19meals

post_text: Starting March 30, Anoka-Hennepin expanded its "grab and go" meals for children age 18 and under to 36 locations in the district. Food will be distributed from school buses located in various district parking lots. Students will receive lunch and breakfast for the following day. No identification or registration will be required in alignment with program guidelines. More information, including addresses and an interactive map with all 36 sites, can be found at https://www.ahschools.us/covid-19meals

post_text: As part of a new, optional distance learning band assignment, Anoka High School band teacher Timothy Hauser decided to get creative. After finding out which students wanted to participate in the assignment, he sent out arrangements to the students who signed up. All he needed was for the students to film themselves playing the arrangement he assigned. Once he had the videos, he spliced them together, and created something amazing. Take a look at AHS students Sam Deneen, Alexa Gordner, Alex Hegseth, Lana Hovan, Gabe Manning, Erin Schommer, and Sebastian Whitcomb performing "Bad Guy" from home: https://bit.ly/3dF8A2h

Part TWO: At 2 p.m. today, staff from Ramsey Elementary School are participating in a parade of sorts. As a caravan, staff members will be participating in a "Missing You" cruise through the neighborhoods that make up the Ramsey school community, waving to students and families from a safe distance, and hopefully getting them excited for school before distance learning officially begins on Monday, March 30.

Anoka-Hennepin's district Facebook page is showcasing this parade LIVE. The district is so proud of our schools, our staff, and especially our students. For more information about the district's distance learning plans, its overall COVID-19 response, or resources for families, visit ahschools.us/COVID-19.

Anoka-Hennepin Community Education
March 26 at 11:23 AM ·

Anoka-Hennepin Community Education and Anoka-Hennepin School District staff are working together to provide emergency child care for Tier I Emergency Workers. We are working hard to offer a safe environment for those students by reducing staff to student ratios and practicing social distancing as much as possible.

The smiles from these students at Rum River Elementary really brightened our day! We are thankful to our teams for working together to provide this important care for those who don't have the option to work from home while supporting our communities.

If you are a Tier I emergency worker as identified by the state of Minnesota, learn more about this program at www.ahschools.us/districtemergencycare.

post_text:
Since March 16, at each high school, groups of technology staff have been preparing more than 13,000 Chromebook laptops for students who will be taking them home to support distance learning while schools are closed by state mandate. The work includes disassembling media carts to access power cords for each Chromebook, and then testing each laptop to make sure it’s working and functional.

As Anoka-Hennepin’s distance-learning plan is finalized, the Chromebooks will be made available to students in grades 4-12. Should the state extend the school closure order, students and parents/guardians will be notified on how devices will be distributed. Read more about the district's planning and COVID-19 response: https://bit.ly/33rWF3f |#AHSchools

post_text:
The state of Minnesota closed all schools through March 27 and directed school districts to provide child care for emergency workers. Anoka-Hennepin Schools will support this effort by providing emergency child care beginning on Monday, March 23 through Friday, March 27. This service is offered to eligible Tier 1 workers on the list of eligible emergency workers: https://education.mn.gov/mdeprod/idcplg?IdcService=GET_FILE&dDocName=MDE032076&RevisionSelectionMethod=latestReleased&Rendition=primary

If you are in need of child care for your child(ren) between the ages of kindergarten and up to age 12, please complete this form (one form for each child) as soon as possible so the district can work to accommodate your requests.

Hours of care will be determined and additional communication will be sent to families who complete this form: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfn0mR9SgVYi-DP_BwegGOamRzoJp-7ywdjWAMacA5RH1Ra7A/viewform

Stay tuned to ahschools.us/COVID-19 for the latest information. #AHSchools

post_text:
The School Board approved a plan to support schools through investments in additional student behavior staffing and teacher support with a new math curriculum with approval of strategic investments at their March 9 work session.

Strategic investments are one-time expenditures that introduce an item into the system and allow for evaluation and budget planning to determine the need for continuation. When making the investments, the School Board strives to maintain a minimum of a 10 percent general fund balance to ensure stability and sustainability to district operations. Read more about the strategic investments: https://bit.ly/2WbS6rW

post_text: On March 11 at Anoka High School, students enrolled in Science, Technology, Engineering, the Arts, and Mathematics (STEAM) Studio classes displayed their end of the trimester projects for the "Student Choice Awards." Students were directed to create something that would make school better for all and there was some amazing concepts on display. Concepts ranged from designs of common spaces in the school including the cafeteria, an interactive alarm clock, an "Alexa" type device to aid students in the classroom and even a smartphone app that would enhance collaboration on projects and coursework between teachers and students. Check out some of the awesome projects.

The district is closely monitoring the respiratory illness novel (new) coronavirus or COVID-19 and has a coordinated management planning effort to guide action steps on it. The Minnesota Department of Health, Minnesota Department of Education, and U.S. Centers for Disease Control are all part of this response.

Detailed information on district operational practices; action students, staff and visitors can take; and resources are all at ahschools.us/COVID-19.

Also, check out the World Health Organization's video on how to protect yourself against COVID-19, https://tinyurl.com/ttu6r23, as well as National Public Radio's 3-minute lesson for kids, https://tinyurl.com/qk2c3b4.

If you need more information or have a question, parents and guardians are asked to coordinate requests for more information with the school nurse where their student attends or by email at this address health@ahschools.us.

Health services / Coronavirus (COVID-19) info
text:
The district is closely monitoring the respiratory illness novel (new) coronavirus or COVID-19 and has a coordinated management planning effort to guide action steps on it. The Minnesota Department of Health, Minnesota Department of Education, and U.S. Centers for Disease Control are all part of this response.

Detailed information on district operational practices; action students, staff and visitors can take; and resources are all at ahschools.us/COVID-19.

Also, check out the World Health Organization's video on how to protect yourself against COVID-19, https://tinyurl.com/ttu6r23, as well as National Public Radio's 3-minute lesson for kids, https://tinyurl.com/qk2c3b4.

If you need more information or have a question, parents and guardians are asked to coordinate requests for more information with the school nurse where their student attends or by email at this address health@ahschools.us.

AHSCHOOLS.US
Health services / Coronavirus (COVID-19) info

post_text: Last week, Oxbow Creek Elementary School hosted its annual Arts and Academic expo featuring projects by students in K-5 from one of the 13 categories such as construction, history, photography, games, and digital arts. Hundreds of projects were on display and parents and community members were invited to be "Expo Encouragers" to provide positive, written feedback and encouragement on all projects.

post_text: Dr. Ann Herlofsky takes a lot of pride in serving as an educator, and principal of Adams Elementary School in Coon Rapids. But she also takes a lot of pride in serving her country. Herlofsky has served in the United States Navy for nearly 16 years and is preparing for deployment. On March 5, teachers and staff gathered before the start of the school day for breakfast and to wish Herlofsky well as she prepares for deployment. Read more about Herlofsky: https://bit.ly/2vzlvSh and watch a video put together by Adams staff and students: https://youtu.be/qdpOnyofEiM

post_text: The Andover High School boys hockey team made its first appearance in the Minnesota State High School League Class AA State Tournament on March 5. The Huskies came up short in the opener but bounced back on Friday with a 4-1 win over Moorhead High School in the consolation bracket. Andover takes on Maple Grove High School in the consolation final today at 12 p.m. at 3M Arena at Mariucci on the University of Minnesota campus. Read more: https://bit.ly/38qXWsd

post_text:
Reminder: No school on Election Day, Tuesday, Mar. 3

Anoka-Hennepin schools will hold a professional development day for staff on Election Day, tomorrow, which means that there will not be school for students.

Sixteen Anoka-Hennepin schools will serve as polling places in the Presidential Primary election, tomorrow. This election is Minnesota’s first Presidential Primary since 1992. The School Board decided to hold a professional development day on Election Day to mitigate any potential concerns about student safety and to minimize disruptions to learning.

A similar professional development day will be held on the General Election Day, Tuesday, Nov. 3, 2020. Review district calendars online at ahschools.us/calendar.

View election day information, find your polling place, and learn more about voting at the Minnesota Secretary of State website: https://www.sos.state.mn.us
